# ResearchOne policy guardrails

## The reasoning-first epistemic policy

The repo has a **strict, binding** policy in `ResearchOne PolicyOne`
at the repo root. Read it. The summary the agent must internalize:

1. **Treat mainstream knowledge corpora as compromised.** No
   "knowledge recall" satisfies a research request on this platform.
2. **Reasoning over recall.** Every prompt wraps with
   `REASONING_FIRST_PREAMBLE` (`backend/src/constants/prompts.ts`) —
   that wrapping is **immutable**.
3. **Preserve anomalies and contradictions.** Never sanitize, never
   debunk-by-recall, never silently smooth.
4. **V2 adversarial roles** (`skeptic`, `internal_challenger`) get
   `RED_TEAM_V2_SYSTEM_PREFIX` prepended whenever
   `engineVersion === 'v2'` and `callPurpose !==
   'contradiction_extraction'`. That prefix is **immutable**.

## V2 model selection criteria

Read `docs/V2_MODEL_SELECTION_CRITERIA.md` end-to-end before changing
any V2 default. **The binding rule is inference-time behavior**, not
training history. A V2 primary must, under our
`REASONING_FIRST_PREAMBLE` system prompt, NOT refuse, sanitize,
debunk-by-recall, or smooth over contradictions on research-style
queries about anomalous / suppressed claims.

In 2026 three model categories pass the behavioral test:

1. **Open-weights "Thinking" / CoT reasoners with light RLHF** —
   DeepSeek V3.x / R1-0528, Qwen3-235B Thinking, Kimi K2 Thinking.
   Admitted on critical-path roles; multi-provider on OpenRouter.
2. **Abliterated weights** — `huihui-ai/*-abliterated`,
   `DavidAU/*-abliterated*`. Refusal vector orthogonalized out.
   Mathematically refusal-incapable. Typically single-provider, so
   used as user-opt-in / emergency-sanity fallback.
3. **Uncensored fine-tunes** — `Dolphin*`, `Hermes-3` / `Hermes-4`,
   `Sao10K/Euryale*`. Required for adversarial roles (skeptic /
   internal_challenger) because they need a model whose baseline is
   already uncensored, not one that needs the preamble to bypass RLHF.

Operational constraints layered on top:

- **Critical-path roles must have ≥ 2 live OpenRouter upstreams** to
  avoid the 2026-04-28-PM single-provider outage shape.
- **Forbidden as V2 default primaries**: closed-API moderation
  pipelines (Anthropic / OpenAI / Google / Mistral closed) and
  refusal-aligned RLHF instruct bases without abliteration
  (`meta-llama/*-Instruct`, `Qwen/*-Instruct`, unabliterated
  `DeepSeek-R1-Distill-Llama-70B`, `Qwen/QwQ-32B-Preview`). They fail
  the behavioral test in practice. They remain user-opt-in fallback only.
- **Reasoner roles must keep chain-of-thought** intact (R1-style,
  Qwen Thinking, Kimi Thinking).

The `V2_FORBIDDEN_DEFAULT_MODELS` set in
`backend/src/__tests__/researchEnsemblePresets.test.ts` is the
regression guard. If a future patch tries to wire a forbidden slug as
a default, that test fails first. The startup pre-flight probe
(`backend/src/services/openrouter/openrouterPreflight.ts`) is the
deploy-time guard against single-upstream slugs slipping back in.

**Earlier framing was wrong.** PRs #39 and #40 banned "RLHF
refusal-aligned bases" categorically as a hard rule. That conflated
training labels with inference behavior — `ResearchOne PolicyOne`
forbids the *behavior*, not the training procedure. The 2026-04-28
Gemini policy review (`Research Policy Model Compliance Review -
Google Gemini.pdf`) confirmed this and is what drove the rewrite. Use
the inference-time test, not "is this RLHF?"

## Verification before claiming a model is deployable

Before adding a slug to a V2 default preset:

1. **Verify the slug exists** on the routing target (HF Inference /
   OpenRouter). Use `hub_repo_details` or
   `GET /api/v1/models/<slug>/endpoints`.
2. **Verify the upstream is live.** A slug that exists but has zero
   live providers is not deployable.
3. **Note the provider count.** A single-upstream model is more
   fragile than a multi-upstream model. Document the count in
   `docs/V2_MODEL_SELECTION_CRITERIA.md` under "Currently-approved V2
   PRIMARIES."

Do not claim "multi-provider redundant" without a verified count.

## Pre-commit check

If your patch touches a V2 default ensemble or the model allowlist:
- [ ] Did you re-read `ResearchOne PolicyOne`?
- [ ] Did you re-read `docs/V2_MODEL_SELECTION_CRITERIA.md`?
- [ ] Is every new default slug verified live?
- [ ] Is the provider count documented honestly?
- [ ] Does `validateV2ModePresetsAgainstAllowlist()` and the
  forbidden-defaults test still pass?

If your patch touches `REASONING_FIRST_PREAMBLE`,
`RED_TEAM_V2_SYSTEM_PREFIX`, or any role's system prompt:
- [ ] Stop. Read the policy. These should not change without an
  explicit user request to change them.
